&lt;p&gt;I was trying to write a Bash script that uses an &lt;code&gt;if&lt;/code&gt; statement.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre class=&quot;lang-bash s-code-block&quot;&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;hljs language-bash&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;hljs-keyword&quot;&gt;if&lt;/span&gt;[&lt;span class=&quot;hljs-variable&quot;&gt;$CHOICE&lt;/span&gt; -eq 1];
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The script was giving me errors until I gave a space before and after &lt;code&gt;[&lt;/code&gt; and before &lt;code&gt;]&lt;/code&gt; as shown below:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre class=&quot;lang-bash s-code-block&quot;&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;hljs language-bash&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;hljs-keyword&quot;&gt;if&lt;/span&gt; [ &lt;span class=&quot;hljs-variable&quot;&gt;$CHOICE&lt;/span&gt; -eq 1 ];
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My question here is, why is the space around the square brackets so important in Bash?&lt;/p&gt;
